'''Doomfist''' is a fictional, [[playable character]] in the 2016 video game ''[[Overwatch (video game)|Overwatch]].'' He is an offensive, [[brawler]]-style character, and uses close-range attacks: a charged punch, uppercut, and slam. Doomfist was released in July 2017 as the title's 25th hero, and the fourth introduced after the game's launch.

''Overwatch''{{'s}} [[Overwatch animated media|announcement video]], in 2014, contained a stray reference to a gauntlet. [[Blizzard Entertainment]] later included the gauntlet in the kit of a full-fledged, playable character. In Doomfist's fictional backstory, the playable character became the third generation to wield the gauntlet, and is presented as a [[villain]] after killing his predecessor and becoming a leader of Talon, the game's nemesis group. The [[Overwatch (digital comic series)|digital comic]] ''Masquerade'' accompanied the character's release.

Fans were excited by the character's reveal, and professional players praised the [[Balance (game design)|balance]] of his move set. Other critics considered Doomfist too vulnerable to be viable, and insufficiently exciting to rekindle the interest of old players.

Doomfist is voiced by [[Sahr Ngaujah]].

== Description ==

Doomfist is an offense character built as a [[brawler]], with close-range, melee attacks from his [[cybernetic]]<!-- {{r|Kotaku: early thoughts}}, if needed --> [[gauntlet (glove)|gauntlet]]. His Rocket Punch is a charged attack that launches Doomfist in the direction of the player's aim. It does extra damage if it pummels the enemy into a wall.{{r|HND: kit}} It is useful for finishing enemies in retreat as well as pushing enemies off edges.{{r|PC Gamer: pros analyze}} The Rising Uppercut punches the enemy with Doomfist into the air, and the Seismic Slam performs a smashing dive to return to the ground. His only non-melee attack is his short-range Hand Cannon, which shoots a shotgun burst of projectiles from the gauntlet's knuckles.{{r|HND: kit}} Its four shots of ammunition regenerate slowly.{{r|HND: kit|PC Gamer: pros analyze}} Doomfist's passive ability regenerates his shields when he deals damage. His ultimate ability, Meteor Strike, launches Doomfist into the air to rain down on a targeted area,{{r|HND: kit}} and complements other ultimate abilities that pull enemies together.{{r|Kotaku: early thoughts}}{{refn|Examples of characters with ultimate abilities that pull enemies together (also known as "crowd-control" ultimates) include [[Zarya (Overwatch)|Zarya]], [[Mei (Overwatch)|Mei]], and [[Reinhardt (Overwatch)|Reinhardt]].{{r|Kotaku: early thoughts}}}}

These moves are designed to be used in flurry combinations. For instance, the player can Seismic Slam an opponent, which pulls in enemies, and progress into a Rising Uppercut, which tosses the opponent into the air. During that toss, the player can charge the Rocket Punch and release as the opponent returns to the ground. Alternatively, the player can launch into the air, pick an opponent to slam, and punch them at close range. The character is built for aggressive playstyles and advanced players<!-- "high skill cap" -->.{{r|PC Gamer: pros analyze}}

Among his advantages, his move combinations contribute to his high mobility, compared to other ''Overwatch'' playable characters. Doomfist can easily reach and neutralize enemies occupying high ground, such as snipers. He is most effective against low-mobility opponents, but susceptible to high-mobility opponents, such as [[Pharah (Overwatch)|Pharah]], [[Soldier: 76]], and [[Sombra (Overwatch)|Sombra]]. Among his disadvantages, Doomfist is dependent on his abilities to escape groups of enemies, leaving the player helpless when his abilities are unavailable (on cooldown or hacked by Sombra). Doomfist's large "hitbox", or area for taking damage, disadvantages him to characters such as [[Reaper (Overwatch)|Reaper]], [[Roadhog (Overwatch)|Roadhog]], and [[Ana (Overwatch)|Ana]]'s sleep dart.{{r|PC Gamer: pros analyze}}

Some of the character's skins relate to his fictional cultural heritage, such as the [[orisha]] gods of the [[Yoruba religion]] and the [[Traditional African masks|African ceremonial mask tradition]].<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Frank |first1=Allegra |title=Overwatch is embracing Doomfist's Nigerian origins in the coolest way |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |date=2017-07-13 |url=https://www.polygon.com/2017/7/13/15965716/overwatch-doomfist-legendary-skins-nigerian |accessdate=2017-07-13 |df=mdy-all |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170713205017/https://www.polygon.com/2017/7/13/15965716/overwatch-doomfist-legendary-skins-nigerian |archivedate=July 13, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last1=Kim |first1=Matt |title=Doomfist's First Legendary Skins are Live on the Overwatch PTR |work=[[USgamer]] |date=2017-07-13 |url=http://www.usgamer.net/articles/doomfists-first-legendary-skins-are-live-on-the-overwatch-ptr |accessdate=2017-07-13 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Doomfist's other aesthetic customization options allude to the boxer [[Muhammad Ali]], the [[Combo (video gaming)|combo sequences]] of [[fighting video game]]s, and other pop culture references.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Frank |first1=Allegra |title=Doomfist's sprays make 'the greatest' references |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |date=2017-07-13 |url=https://www.polygon.com/2017/7/13/15959886/overwatch-doomfist-sprays |accessdate=2017-07-13 |df=mdy-all |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170714034404/https://www.polygon.com/2017/7/13/15959886/overwatch-doomfist-sprays |archivedate=July 14, 2017 }}</ref>{{r|HND: sprays}}

== Development ==

{{external media |video1=[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UXCNNDHboho The 2014 cinematic], in which the game was first announced and Doomfist's gauntlet first appeared |video2=[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lBaWAxeHcw0 Doomfist character preview with developer commentary]}}

Doomfist was a stray reference in ''Overwatch''{{'}}s original [[Overwatch animated media|animated short]] whose obsessive popularity with fans led the development team to expand his lore with in-game references in the game's Numbani map.{{r|IGN: official teaser|IGN: mock audition}} In the cinematic video used to announce the game in 2014, a boy is excited to see Doomfist's gauntlet on display behind glass at the Overwatch museum.{{r|HND: ever}} Doomfist's gauntlet was a plot device, and the developers had not planned to create a character to wield it. ''Overwatch'' Creative Director [[Chris Metzen]] played with compound nouns to give the gauntlet a name reminiscent of a shotgun. The developers expanded the gauntlet into a Doomfist character in bits. In particular, they decided to use the gauntlet as the centerpiece for the game's Numbani environment, in which the gauntlet is encased in the map's objective, the payload, to be delivered to a Doomfist exhibit at a museum. By late 2015, the team decided Doomfist would be a generational hero, like that of superhero universes, were he to be a full-fledged playable character,{{r|PC Gamer: as it goes}} the fourth additional character to be added to game,{{r|Engadget: fourth}} and 25th on the roster.{{r|Polygon: finally}}

In designing the character, Blizzard's Geoff Goodman said they crafted Doomfist as an "ode to the [[fighting game|fighting genre]]", both in his skill kit and in concept art.{{r|GS: SDCC}} Though Blizzard tried to keep all of his attacks as melee, they found, as they had with Genji, that Doomfist needed some type of ranged attack to make him playable; an early attack had been a phantom punch that would have been launched from his fist.{{r|GS: SDCC 2}} Doomfist had also be considered as a Tank class, but Blizzard did not want to make the mistake again of having a high-health character with powerful attacks as they had initially with Roadhog at the game's introduction.{{r|GS: SDCC 2}} At one point during development, Doomfist would have been able to pick up enemies and use them as [[human shield]]s or to throw them, but Blizzard dropped this as he was not supposed to be a wrestler or [[luchador]], according to Goodman.{{r|GS: SDCC 2}} They also dropped an ability for him to grab pieces of the ground and throw them.{{r|GS: SDCC 2}} His ultimate ability was originally designed for [[Orisa (Overwatch)|Orisa]], the character introduced prior to Doomfist.{{r|GS: SDCC 2}}

[[File:Sahr Ngaujah Last Resort NYC 2012 Copyright Rameen Gasery.jpg|thumb|upright=.8|Doomfist voice actor [[Sahr Ngaujah]], pictured in 2012]]

Actor and former [[American football]] player [[Terry Crews]] generated support on social media in his bid to [[video game voice actor|voice the character]], which included a mock audition, a visit to the developer's headquarters, an endorsement from fellow actor [[Dwayne Johnson]], and a fan campaign.{{r|Polygon: heartbreak|Kotaku: excited|GamesRadar: YES, PLEASE GOD YES}} The character was ultimately voiced by [[Sahr Ngaujah]], who previously appeared in ''[[Money Monster]]'' and ''[[Stomp the Yard]]''.{{r|IGN: in PTR}} Blizzard's Michael Chu explained that when they were casting for Doomfist specifically looking for "something very specific given his role in the game", Ngaujah's audition significantly impressed them, along with his ability to deliver many different "flavors" that they needed for the character.{{r|GS: SDCC}} Crews ultimately felt that Ngaujah was a better fit for Doomfist, and was pleased to have been included, instead, in [[Microsoft]]'s ''[[Crackdown 3]]''.{{r|PC Gamer: Crews Crackdown}} Chu did not rule out using Crews elsewhere within ''Overwatch''.{{r|GS: SDCC}}

In the lead-up to Blizzard's official announcement of the playable character, the developers teased his release by modifying the Doomfist gauntlet in Numbani to appear to be stolen from its glass case.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Skrebels |first1=Joe |title=More Evidence of New Hero Doomfist Emerges in Latest Overwatch Update |work=[[IGN]] |date=2017-02-08 |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2017/02/08/more-evidence-of-new-hero-doomfist-emerges-in-latest-overwatch-update |accessdate=2017-07-10 |df=mdy-all |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170318115538/http://www.ign.com/articles/2017/02/08/more-evidence-of-new-hero-doomfist-emerges-in-latest-overwatch-update |archivedate=March 18, 2017 }}</ref>{{r|Kotaku: excited}} Blizzard finally confirmed the Doomfist's development with a [[teaser trailer]] in early July 2017, a week after news of the release leaked through the game's [[crash log]]s.{{r|IGN: official teaser}} The reveal cinematic was drawn in an anime-style by Wolf Smoke Studio, based in Shanghai, who had previously expressed and rallied interest in developing an anime in the game's fictional universe.{{r|Polygon: Wolf Smoke}} Blizzard also sent an official Doomfist [[cosplayer]] to the [[San Diego Comic-Con]] and [[Overwatch World Cup 2017|Overwatch World Cup Sydney qualifier]].{{r|Polygon: cosplay|Kotaku: cosplay}} Soon after the reveal, Doomfist became playable on the game's test servers,{{r|IGN: in PTR}} where some of the character's powers were rebalanced to reduce punch distance and vertical mobility.{{r|HND: launch nerf}} The character was released for all platforms on July 27, 2017.{{r|GS: live}}

== Lore ==

{{external media |video1=[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vaZfZFNuOpI Doomfist origin story], an official, animated short}}

Doomfist is presented as a "generational" character who, like [[The Green Lantern]] or [[The Flash]], has passed through two generational eras in which he was known to the fictional world as "The Savior" and "The Scourge".{{r|IGN: mock audition}} The playable Doomfist is the character's third incarnation, labeled "The Successor" as the third person to be called "Doomfist".{{r|IGN: real villain}}

Doomfist is one of the villains of the ''Overwatch'' fictional universe.{{r|IGN: real villain}} In the backstory of the third Doomfist, Akande Ogundimu is presented as the villainous heir to a [[prosthetics]] company in Nigeria who splits his time between expanding the company and [[martial arts]] training. During the game's "Omnic War" between humans and rogue Omnic robots, Ogundimu lost his right arm. His prosthetic replacement impressed the second Doomfist (Akinjide Adeyemi), who then trained Ogundimu as his successor, but the student later killed his teacher to claim the gauntlet for himself. Ogundimu became a leader<!-- along with Reaper, Sombra, Widowmaker --> of the Talon group, the nemesis organization to Overwatch, and advocates for his belief that forces of conflict will strengthen humanity. At some point prior to the game's present, Overwatch's [[Winston (Overwatch)|Winston]], a playable character from the game, defeats Doomfist and puts the titular gauntlet behind glass in the Overwatch museum, as referenced in the original ''Overwatch'' announcement video.{{r|HND: ever}} Blizzard's first teaser for Doomfist's release shows a fictional news report about Talon freeing Doomfist from prison to steal the gauntlet.{{r|IGN: in PTR|Polygon: finally}} Blizzard had modified the Numbani level during its release of Orisa, the previous playable character released for the game, to imply that Doomfist had attacked the city and stolen the gauntlet; notably, the payload casing had been broken open and the gauntlet missing.{{r|Polygon: something's happening}}

[[Overwatch (digital comic series)|A digital comic]] accompanied the playable character's release, featuring Doomfist in a [[James Bond]]-esque casino setting. ''Masquerade'' establishes the character's motivations and competition following his release from prison.{{r|HND: Masquerade|HND: Masquerade costumes}}

== Reception ==

Upon Doomfist's official announcement, ''[[Kotaku]]'' reported the fan reaction as "beyond excited".{{r|Kotaku: react}} Fan anticipation for the character rivaled that for [[Sombra (Overwatch)|Sombra]], a character released the previous year{{r|IGN: real villain}} with a prolonged reveal period.{{r|PC Gamer: on PTR}} Players had hoped for the release of Doomfist each time Blizzard had revealed an additional character for the game.{{r|Kotaku: react}} ''Polygon'' wrote that Doomfist's announcement cinematic, drawn in an anime style, was the best in the series to date.{{r|Polygon: Wolf Smoke}}<!-- {{r|Kotaku: react}} thought it was "fun", though is that noteworthy --> Fans who had lobbied for Terry Crews to play Doomfist's voice were disappointed to discover his absence, but Sahr Ngaujah's performance was praised at the time of Doomfist's formal unveiling,{{r|Polygon: heartbreak}} and fans received the character positively anyway.{{r|Kotaku: react}} Blizzard's choice of Ngaujah over the higher profile Crews also meant that the voice actor would be more available to reappear for additional recording and other game community events.{{r|HND: famous}} Doomfist also fulfilled ''Overwatch''{{'s}} sore lack of a [[supervillain]], according to ''IGN'', in a cast of other morally ambiguous but tragic and redeemable characters. The critic anticipated Doomfist as the start of Blizzard making Talon into a villainous organization à la [[Legion of Doom]] (''[[Justice League]]'') or [[Masters of Evil]] (''[[Avengers (comics)|Avengers]]'').{{r|IGN: real villain}}

''Heroes Never Die'', an ''Overwatch''-specific news spinoff site by ''[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]'', wrote that Doomfist's style was wholly unlike that of the other characters, and created a "feast or famine" scenario in which the character is only helpful when engaged in risky, aggressive play.{{r|HND: guide}} The site expected Doomfist's release to affect team character selections to maximize Doomfist's strengths, weaknesses, and synergies.{{r|HND: synergies}} ''PC Gamer'' praised Doomfist's [[Balance (game design)|balance]] against the other characters just prior to his launch. Professional players complimented the addition of a strong, counterable character to disrupt the common, uncounterable characters normally played in the professional circuit. Another commended the idea of fighting game-style combos in a first-person shooter for adding an additional skill ceiling for players to pursue.{{r|PC Gamer: pros analyze}} ''Kotaku'', however, considered Doomfist a better fit for a ''[[Marvel vs. Capcom]]'' fighting game than ''Overwatch'', and bemoaned the character's vulnerability to snipers, low health, and lack of escape options, which made him less threatening or even unrewarding.{{r|Kotaku: early thoughts}} Even as Doomfist's design was neat, ''[[Waypoint (website)|Waypoint]]''{{'s}} critic thought, the character was not exciting or enough of an [[extrinsic motivator]] to reclaim players who had dropped out from its player base.{{r|Waypoint: won't}} Other reviewers, however, found simple joy in pulling off punches and combos.{{r|Engadget: review|Kotaku: early thoughts}}

At the time of Doomfist's release, the ''Overwatch'' meta-game was favoring "dive" compositions, using a character that can jump over a great distance like Winston or D.Va. Players using these characters would self-sacrifice themselves by jumping into or behind an enemy front-line, and do as much damage as possible, distracting that team from a major push. About a month after Doomfist's addition, the "dive" strategy had become readily countered as Doomfist can quickly eliminate either the singular threat or the oncoming group particularly when coupled with crowd-control skills like Zarya's or Reinhardt's ultimates.{{r|PC Gamer: Doomfist meta}}

