{{Infobox cemetery | name = Elesavetgrad Cemetery | image = Elesavetgrad Chapel Mosaic Install.png | imagesize = 200 | caption = Mosaics being installed on the Elesavetgrad chapel | map_type = United States Washington, D.C. east | map_caption = Location within Washington, D.C. | established = December 1911 | country = United States | location = Washington, D.C. | coordinates = {{coord|38|50|54|N|76|59|07|W|region:US-DC|display=inline}} | type = [[Jewish cemetery|Jewish]] | style = | owner = | size = {{Convert|2.6|acre}} | graves = | interments = | leases = | website = | findagraveid= 2272634 }} The '''Elesavetgrad Cemetery''' DCHBA is a 2.6 acre Jewish cemetery located in [[Washington, D.C. (southeast)|Southeast]] [[Washington, D.C.]] The cemetery was established in December 1911. This cemetery is adjacent to the Ohev Sholom, Adas Israel, [[Bet Mishpachah Cemetery|Bet Mishpachah]] and Washington Hebrew cemeteries.
==History== The cemetery was founded in 1911. The name is derived from the [[English language|English]] equivalent of [[Kropyvnytskyi#Name origin|Elesavetgrad]], [[Ukraine]], the [[History of the Jews in Ukraine|ancestral home]] to many of the founding members.<ref>"Elesavetgrad Cemetery DCHBA pamphlet" Pamphlet published by the officers and sales office. No date noted on pamphlet.</ref>
