{{for|the film|Lunch Meat (film)}} {{redirect|Cold cut|the English DJ duo|Coldcut||Cold Cuts (disambiguation)}} {{undue weight|date=January 2018}} {{Infobox prepared food | name = Lunch meat | image = Cold cuts.jpg | image_size = 250px | caption = A tray of assorted lunch meats with pickles and tomatoes. | alternate_name = Cold cuts, luncheon meats, sandwich meats, cooked meats, sliced meats, cold meats, deli meats | main_ingredient = [[Meat]] }}
'''Lunch meats'''—also known as '''cold cuts''', '''luncheon meats''', '''cooked meats''', '''sliced meats''', '''cold meats''' and '''deli meats'''—are precooked or [[Curing (food preservation)|cured]] meat, often [[sausage]]s or [[meatloaf|meat loaves]], that are sliced and served cold or hot on [[sandwich]]es or on party trays.<ref name=Today>{{cite web|title=The 5 things you need to know about deli meats|url=http://www.today.com/id/16361276/ns/today-food/t/things-you-need-know-about-deli-meats/#.UUVfpXBUOxI|work=Today Food|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=17 March 2013|author=Phil Lempert|date=27 December 2006}}</ref> They can be bought pre-sliced in [[vacuum packing|vacuum packs]] at a [[supermarket]] or [[grocery store]], or they can be purchased at a [[delicatessen]] or deli counter, where they might be sliced to order. Unsliced, [[canning|canned]] lunch meats are sold under brands such as [[Spam (food)|Spam]] and [[Treet]].
== Health == Most pre-sliced lunch meats are higher in [[fat]], [[nitrates]], and [[sodium]] than those that are sliced to order, as a larger exposed surface requires stronger preservatives.<ref name="Today" /> As a result, processed meats significantly contribute to incidence of [[Cardiovascular disease|heart disease]] and [[Diabetes insipidus|diabetes]], even more so than [[red meat]].<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Unprocessed red and processed meats and risk of coronary artery disease and type 2 diabetes--an updated review of the evidence|journal = Current Atherosclerosis Reports|date = 2012-12-01|issn = 1534-6242|pmc = 3483430|pmid = 23001745|pages = 515–524|volume = 14|issue = 6|doi = 10.1007/s11883-012-0282-8|first = Renata|last = Micha|first2 = Georgios|last2 = Michas|first3 = Dariush|last3 = Mozaffarian}}</ref>
A prospective study following 448,568 people across Europe showed a positive association between processed [[meat consumption]] and mortality, due to cardiovascular diseases and [[cancer]].<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Meat consumption and mortality--results from the European Prospective Investigation into Cancer and Nutrition|journal = BMC Medicine|date = 2013-01-01|issn = 1741-7015|pmc = 3599112|pmid = 23497300|pages = 63|volume = 11|doi = 10.1186/1741-7015-11-63|first = Sabine|last = Rohrmann|first2 = Kim|last2 = Overvad|first3 = H. Bas|last3 = Bueno-de-Mesquita|first4 = Marianne U.|last4 = Jakobsen|first5 = Rikke|last5 = Egeberg|first6 = Anne|last6 = Tjønneland|first7 = Laura|last7 = Nailler|first8 = Marie-Christine|last8 = Boutron-Ruault|first9 = Françoise|last9 = Clavel-Chapelon}}</ref> Similarly, a prospective study in United States following half a million people concluded a similar association with death and increased processed meat consumption.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Meat intake and mortality: a prospective study of over half a million people|journal = Archives of Internal Medicine|date = 2009-03-23|issn = 1538-3679|pmc = 2803089|pmid = 19307518|pages = 562–571|volume = 169|issue = 6|doi = 10.1001/archinternmed.2009.6|first = Rashmi|last = Sinha|first2 = Amanda J.|last2 = Cross|first3 = Barry I.|last3 = Graubard|first4 = Michael F.|last4 = Leitzmann|first5 = Arthur|last5 = Schatzkin}}</ref> The [[World Cancer Research Fund International]] guidelines on [[cancer prevention]] recommend avoiding all [[processed meat]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Animal foods {{!}} World Cancer Research Fund International|url = http://wcrf.org/int/research-we-fund/cancer-prevention-recommendations/animal-foods|website = wcrf.org|accessdate = 2015-12-17}}</ref>
== Safety == The US [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] advises that those over 50 reheat lunch meats to "steaming hot" {{convert|165|°F|°C|0|abbr=on}} and use them within four days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/yourlife/health/medical/2011-05-04-listeria-cdc-lunch-meat_n.htm |title=CDC: Over 50? Heat cold cuts to 165 degrees to avoid listeria |publisher=USATODAY.com}}</ref>
== Regional differences == {{refimprove|section|date=July 2018}}
=== Commonwealth countries === In [[The Commonwealth|Commonwealth]] countries, luncheon meat specifically refers to products that can include [[mechanically reclaimed meat]] and [[offal]]. In these countries, the terms "cold meats", "cooked meats", "deli meats", or "sliced meats" are used, instead.
=== Latin America ===
In [[Guatemala]], a lunch meat is a traditional dish eaten in November. It is eaten the first and second day of the month to celebrate ''El día de Todos los Santos'' ([[All Saints' Day]]) and ''El día de Todos los Difuntos'' ([[All Souls' Day]]). The two types are red and white.
=== Central Europe === The product got more popular after investigation what it contains. E.g. LUNCHEON MEAT TULIP (made in Denmark) is not made of 70% of meat as expected (base on country standard), but contains 18% of pork meat, 39% of chicken mechanically separated meat, 18% of pork mechanically separated meat.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.novinky.cz/domaci/411702-velky-test-lunchmeatu-tohle-cteni-chce-silny-zaludek.html|title=Velký test lunchmeatů. Tohle čtení chce silný žaludek|work=Novinky.cz|access-date=2017-07-20|language=cs-CZ}}</ref>
