{{short description|Russian multiple world record holding freediver }} {{Eastern Slavic name|Vadimovna|Molchanova}} {{Infobox sportsperson | image = Molchanova Natalia 1, Danmark, Aarhus, 5th Individual freediving World Championship, 2009.jpg | caption = Natalia Molchanova at the 2009 Freediving World Championships | birth_date = {{Birth date|1962|05|08||df=y}} | birth_place = [[Ufa]], [[Bashkortostan]], [[Soviet Union]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|2015|08|02|1962|05|08||df=y}} | death_place = [[Ibiza]], Spain | residence = Moscow<ref name=r1/> | sport = [[Freediving]] | club = Krokodil, Moscow }}
'''Natalia Vadimovna Molchanova''' ({{lang-ru|Наталья Вадимовна Молчанова}}; 8 May 1962 – 2 August 2015) was a Russian champion [[Freediving|free diver]], multiple world record holder,<ref name=nytimes/> and the former president of the Russian Free Dive Federation. She has been described as "possibly the world’s greatest freediver".<ref>{{cite news|title=Free-diving: Blue hole, black hole: A story of hubris and obsession|url=https://www.economist.com/news/books-and-arts/21693552-story-hubris-and-obsession-blue-hole-black-hole|accessdate=27 February 2016|work=[[The Economist]]|date=27 February 2016}}</ref>
On 2 August 2015 she went missing giving a private lesson for a Russian,<ref name=nytimes/> and is presumed to be dead after search efforts were abandoned on 5 August.<ref>espnW news [http://espn.go.com/espnw/news-commentary/article/13379985/underwater-search-ends-free-diver-natalia-molchanova-spain]</ref>
==Personal life== Molchanova was born in 1962 in [[Ufa]], [[Bashkortostan]], then part of the [[Soviet Union]].<ref name=r2>Oksana Gredzheva. [http://old.free-diving.ru/parser.php?r_id=82&p_id=28&c_id=164&view_msg=1&a_id=471 Чемпионка мира-2005 по фридайвингу Наталья МОЛЧАНОВА]. free-diving.ru (interview in Russian)</ref> Molchanova had a son [[Alexey Molchanov|Alexey]] and daughter Oksana.<ref name="nytimes"/>
==Career== Molchanova was the world's most decorated free diver ever, holding 41 world records at the time of her presumed death and winning 23 gold medals during her lengthy career.<ref name="nbcnews">{{cite news|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/natalia-molchanova-freediving-champion-missing-feared-dead-n404331|title=Natalia Molchanova, Freediving Champion, Missing and Feared Dead|date=5 August 2015|accessdate=5 August 2015|agency=NBC News}}</ref> At the [[AIDA_International#History|2007 Freediving World Championships]] in [[Maribor]], [[Slovenia]], her winning time in the static discipline was better than the winning male gold medal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/news/natalia-molchanova-worlds-most-successful-freedriver-is-missing-and-feared-dead-after-disappearing-in-mediterranean-10438926.html|title=Natalia Molchanova: World's most successful free-diver missing and feared dead after disappearing in Mediterranean|work=The Independent|date=4 August 2015|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref> In September 2009, she became the first woman to pass 100 meters (328 ft.) diving with constant weight, in a dive to 101 meters (331 ft.) in [[Sharm el Sheikh]], [[Egypt]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.deeperblue.com/new-world-record-molchanova-cwt-101m/|title=New World Record – Molchanova CWT 101m|agency=Deeper Blue|date=24 September 2009|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref> Molchanova was also the first woman to dive on one breath through the [[Blue Hole (Red Sea)|Blue Hole]] arch in [[Dahab]], Egypt.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/world-news/natalia-molchanova-freewater-diving-champion-6194341|title=Natalia Molchanova: Freewater diving champion missing presumed dead following practice session in Ibiza|date=4 August 2015|accessdate=5 August 2015|work=Mirror}}</ref> Her record was a dive of 127 metres (417 ft.).<ref>The Daily Telegraph, Friday 9 October 2015, Obituary [paper only], p.33</ref>
She first trained in swimming, but semi-retired for approximately 20 years after giving birth. She resumed training, aged 40, and shifted from swimming to free diving. Her first free diving competition was the 2003 Russian championships in Moscow, where she set a national record. Her son is also a prominent free diving competitor. Molchanova later worked as a free diving instructor at the [[Russian State University of Physical Education, Sport, Youth and Tourism]].<ref name=r2/>
==Disappearance== On 2 August 2015, she was reported missing after giving a private lesson dive near [[Ibiza]], [[Spain]].<ref name="nytimes"/> She went down to a depth of 40 metres (131 ft.), not as deep as normal, but caught by a current, without weights, she is thought to have been taken down. She never came up for air. Initial rescue and recovery efforts were unsuccessful.<ref name="nytimes"/> As of 4 August, search and rescue efforts continued, but she was presumed dead by the search party, including her son [[Alexey Molchanov]].<ref>{{Cite news|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/05/sports/natalia-molchanova-champion-free-diver-is-missing-near-ibiza.html|title = Champion diver is missing|last = |first = |date = |work = |access-date = |via = }}</ref><ref name="nytimes">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/05/sports/natalia-molchanova-champion-free-diver-is-missing-near-ibiza.html?_r=1 | title=Free Diver Natalia Molchanova Descends for Fun, Then Vanishes | publisher=[[New York Times]] | date=4 August 2015 | accessdate=5 August 2015 | last=Skolnick | first=Adam}}</ref><ref>Wilkinson, Alec, [http://www.newyorker.com/news/sporting-scene/the-disappearance-of-the-worlds-greatest-free-diver The Disappearance of the World’s Greatest Free Diver], New Yorker, August 8, 2015</ref>
The Spanish [[Civil Code]] provides that a missing person by [[shipwreck]] or amid a dangerous activity [[Declared death in absentia|shall be declared deceased in absentia]] three months after a missing report.<ref>Spanish Civil Code [http://civil.udg.es/normacivil/estatal/CC/1T8.htm]</ref>
