{{Infobox person | name = Steven Kanumba | image = Steven_Kanumba.jpg | image_size = | caption = | birth_name = Steven Charles Kanumba | birth_date = {{birth date|1984|01|08|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Shinyanga]], [[Tanzania]] | death_date = {{death date and age|2012|04|07|1984|01|08|df=yes}}<ref name=fresh /> | death_place = [[Dar es Salaam]], [[Tanzania]] | death_cause = Brain concussion | residence = Tanzania | other_names = Kanumba the Great | known_as = Kanumba | education = | employer = | occupation = Actor, singer, writer, director, producer, comedian | title = Steven Kanumba | height = | weight = | nationality = Tanzanian }} '''Steven Charles Kanumba''' (8 January 1984 – 7 April 2012) was a [[Tanzania]]n actor and director. Kanumba died in 2012 at the age of 28, for which actress [[Elizabeth Michael]] was convicted of [[involuntary manslaughter]] and sentenced two years in prison in November 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/Africa/News/tanzanian-movie-star-jailed-for-death-of-famous-lover-20171113|title=Tanzanian movie star jailed for death of famous lover|work=News24|access-date=2018-01-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mobile.thecitizen.co.tz/news/Lulu-slapped-with-two-year-jail-term-for-killing-Kanumba/2304482-4184836-format-xhtml-2o73vx/index.html|title=Lulu slapped with two-year jail term for killing Kanumba|publisher=|accessdate=17 August 2018}}</ref> Over 30,000 people were estimated to have attended his funeral.<ref name=thousands>{{cite web|title=Kanumba funeral: Thousands mourn Tanzanian actor|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-17662920|publisher=BBC|accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref> He was described as "Tanzania's most popular film star",<ref name="thousands"/> and appeared in [[Nollywood]] films.
==Early life== Kanumba was born into a [[Sukuma people|Sukuma]] family in the [[Shinyanga Region]] in Northern Tanzania.<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography|url=http://www.kanumba.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=10&Itemid=2|accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref> His father was Charles Kanumba and his mother was Flora Mutegoa.<ref name=fresh>{{cite news|title=Fresh revelations in Kanumba death probe|url=http://thecitizen.co.tz/news/4-national-news/21356-fresh-revelations-in-kanumba-death-probe.html|accessdate=10 April 2012|newspaper=The Citizen Daily|date=9 April 2012|author=Songa wa Songa}}</ref> Kanumba had three older sisters. He began his studies at Bugoyi Primary School and continued with his secondary studies at Mwadui Secondary School, later transferring to Vosa Mission Secondary School. He joined Jitegemee High School for his high level education. He spoke three languages fluently: [[Swahili language|Swahili]], [[Sukuma language|Sukuma]] and English.
==Career== Kanumba began acting in the 1990s in church productions. In 2002, he joined the theater group Kaole Arts Group. He appeared in the television soap operas ''Jahazi'' and ''Dira'' and made his film debut in ''Haviliki''. In 2006 he met Nazz who gave him advice and further connections for his career. He appeared in ''Dar 2 Lagos'', a film by Mtitu Game that used both Tanzanian and Nigerian actors and crew.<ref name=p86>{{cite book|last=Saur|first=Mahir|title=Viewing African Cinema in the Twenty-First Century: Art Films and the Nollywood Video Revolution|page=86|date=2010|publisher=Ohio University Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cH0DaVXW0JMC&dq=Steven+Kanumba&source=gbs_navlinks_s|display-authors=etal}}</ref> He also appeared in the films ''She is My Sister'', ''This Is It'', and ''Love Gamble''. In 2009, he was a special celebrity guest on ''[[Big Brother Africa (season 4)|Big Brother Africa 4]]''.
In 2011, Kanumba was named an [[Oxfam]] GROW Ambassador.<ref>{{cite news|title=Steven Kanumba on Oxfam's GROW campaign in Tanzania|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oSPSS4QEeU8|accessdate=10 April 2012|newspaper=Oxfam East Africa|date=5 June 2011}}</ref> Shortly before his death he had been preparing for his first [[Hollywood]] film role,<ref name=fresh/> although he was already "Tanzania's most popular film star"<ref name=thousands /> and appeared in [[Nollywood]] films.
==Death== Kanumba died after he fell in his bedroom on 7 April 2012, apparently from a blow to the head.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecitizen.co.tz/News/-/1840340/1818490/-/98rjnmz/-/index.html |title=Fresh revelations in Kanumba death probe - News |publisher=The Citizen |date= |accessdate=2018-08-17}}</ref> His 17-year-old girlfriend at that time, actress [[Elizabeth Michael]], also known as Lulu, was questioned. She denied causing the death of Kanumba.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecitizen.co.tz/News/-/1840350/1831316/-/cxmra5z/-/index.html|title=State lines up 9 witnesses in Lulu manslaughter case|date=21 December 2012|publisher=|accessdate=17 August 2018}}</ref> Kanumba was taken unconscious to Muhimbili National Referral Hospital where he was declared dead.<ref name=thousands /> In 2017, Lulu was convicted of involuntary manslaughter for his death and sentenced to two years in prison.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tanzania actress Lulu Elizabeth slapped with two year jail term for killing bongo star Steven Kanumba|url=https://www.sde.co.ke/article/2001260099/tanzania-actress-lulu-slapped-with-two-year-jail-term-for-killing-kanumba|website=Daily Nation|accessdate=13 November 2017}}</ref> Her sentence was then changed from two years imprisonment to community services and she was [http://www.mwananchi.co.tz/habari/Lulu-aachiwa--huru--Dar/1597578-4560438-t1qybqz/index.html released from jail] in May 12, 2018 after serving at least a year in jail.
His funeral was attended by around 30,000 people including the first lady of Tanzania, [[Salma Kikwete]],<ref name=club>{{cite web|title=Farewell Kanumba The Great: Photos from the escort and final mass at Leaders Club|url=http://www.bongo5.com/farewell-kanumba-the-great-photos-from-the-escort-and-final-mass-at-leaders-club-04-2012/|publisher=Bongo 5|accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref> Vice President Dr. [[Mohamed Gharib Bilal]], and the minister for culture and sport, [[Emmanuel Nchimbi]].<ref>[http://www.ippmedia.com/frontend/index.php?l=40423 Kanumba laid to rest], Mohammed Ugasa, 11 April 2012</ref> Kanumba was buried in [[Kinondoni]] Cemetery.<ref name=fresh/>
